You said:
Can you provide shell script for testing provisioning of azure compute gallery inage which is built as generalized image
ChatGPT said:
Perfect question 🚀

If you want to test whether a generalized Azure Compute Gallery (ACG) image provisions successfully, you can automate this with a shell script.

This script will:

Create a resource group (test only).

Create a VM from your ACG image (generalized).

Wait for provisioning to complete.

Check the provisioningState and osProvisioningState.

Delete everything (optional cleanup).

🔹 Shell Script: Test ACG Generalized Image Provisioning
#!/bin/bash

# ==============================
# CONFIGURATION (EDIT THESE)
# ==============================
RG_NAME="TestACGProvisionRG"
LOCATION="eastus"                          # Change as per your region
VM_NAME="TestACGVM"
SIZE="Standard_B2s"                        # Small test size
USER="azureuser"                           # New user injected during provisioning
PASSWORD="P@ssword1234!"                   # Strong password
GALLERY_NAME="MyGallery"
IMAGE_DEF_NAME="MyImageDef"
IMAGE_VERSION="1.0.0"

# ==============================
# SCRIPT START
# ==============================

echo ">> Creating resource group..."
az group create -n $RG_NAME -l $LOCATION

echo ">> Creating VM from ACG generalized image..."
az vm create \
  --resource-group $RG_NAME \
  --name $VM_NAME \
  --image "/subscriptions/$(az account show --query id -o tsv)/resourceGroups/$RG_NAME/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/$GALLERY_NAME/images/$IMAGE_DEF_NAME/versions/$IMAGE_VERSION" \
  --admin-username $USER \
  --admin-password $PASSWORD \
  --size $SIZE \
  --authentication-type password \
  --verbose

echo ">> Waiting for provisioning result..."
sleep 60   # Give it a minute to initialize

# Check provisioning state
PROV_STATE=$(az vm get-instance-view \
  --resource-group $RG_NAME \
  --name $VM_NAME \
  --query "instanceView.statuses[?starts_with(code,'ProvisioningState/')].displayStatus" -o tsv)

OS_PROV_STATE=$(az vm get-instance-view \
  --resource-group $RG_NAME \
  --name $VM_NAME \
  --query "instanceView.statuses[?starts_with(code,'ProvisioningState/')].message" -o tsv)

echo "======================================="
echo "Provisioning State: $PROV_STATE"
echo "OS Provisioning State: $OS_PROV_STATE"
echo "======================================="

if [[ "$PROV_STATE" == "Provisioning succeeded" ]]; then
  echo "✅ VM provisioned successfully from generalized ACG image"
else
  echo "❌ VM provisioning failed (likely agent/generalization issue)"
fi

# Optional: Cleanup
read -p "Do you want to delete the test resource group $RG_NAME? (y/n): " confirm
if [[ $confirm == "y" ]]; then
  echo ">> Deleting resource group..."
  az group delete -n $RG_NAME --yes --no-wait
fi
🔹 How It Works
The script deploys a VM from your generalized ACG image.

Because it’s generalized, Azure will inject the new username/password you pass.

If the VM agent is missing, or if the OS wasn’t generalized → provisioning will time out (and you’ll see it in the script output).

✅ Usage
chmod +x test_acg_generalized.sh
./test_acg_generalized.sh
