ChatGPT said:
Exactly ✅ you nailed it.

If the image inside your Azure Compute Gallery (ACG) is marked osState=generalized, but the source VHD/VM wasn’t properly prepared with agent + generalized OS, then:

When the script tries to create a VM, Azure will attempt OS Provisioning (inject username, hostname, SSH/password).

That requires the Azure VM Agent to be installed and running.

If the agent is missing (or the OS wasn’t generalized with waagent / sysprep), the VM will boot but never signal success → provisioning sits in Creating then fails with:

