🔹 Why This Differs From VHD/Managed Disk Boot
From VHD / managed disk → Azure just boots the OS "as-is".

No need for agent.

No generalization.

Works even with a raw disk.

From ACG generalized → Azure must perform provisioning → agent + generalized OS required.

🔹 So, To Make Your Script Work
Before you ever capture into ACG as --os-state generalized, you must prepare the VM:

Linux (Ubuntu/CentOS/RHEL)
# Ensure VM agent installed
sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install -y walinuxagent
sudo systemctl enable waagent
sudo systemctl start waagent

# Deprovision and generalize
sudo waagent -deprovision+user -force
Windows
# Ensure Azure VM Agent installed (comes pre-installed on Azure Marketplace images)

# Run Sysprep
C:\Windows\System32\Sysprep\Sysprep.exe /generalize /oobe /shutdown
Then capture it into ACG with:

az sig image-version create \
  --resource-group MyRG \
  --gallery-name MyGallery \
  --gallery-image-definition MyImageDef \
  --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \
  --os-vhd-uri <your-vhd-uri> \
  --os-state generalized
✅ Bottom Line
Generalized ACG images → require VM Agent + generalized OS.

Specialized ACG images → no agent needed, Azure won’t inject credentials.

