Perfect 👍 Let’s fix the test workflow so you don’t waste time trying to provision a generalized ACG image that’s missing the agent or wasn’t generalized.

Here’s an updated shell script:

🔹 Script: Validate and Test ACG Generalized Image
#!/bin/bash

# ==============================
# CONFIGURATION (EDIT THESE)
# ==============================
RG_NAME="TestACGProvisionRG"
LOCATION="eastus"
VM_NAME="TestACGVM"
SIZE="Standard_B2s"
USER="azureuser"
PASSWORD="P@ssword1234!"
GALLERY_NAME="MyGallery"
IMAGE_DEF_NAME="MyImageDef"
IMAGE_VERSION="1.0.0"

# ==============================
# SCRIPT START
# ==============================

# Build full ACG image ID
ACG_IMAGE_ID="/subscriptions/$(az account show --query id -o tsv)/resourceGroups/$RG_NAME/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/$GALLERY_NAME/images/$IMAGE_DEF_NAME/versions/$IMAGE_VERSION"

echo ">> Checking image definition OS state..."
OS_STATE=$(az sig image-definition show \
  --resource-group $RG_NAME \
  --gallery-name $GALLERY_NAME \
  --gallery-image-definition $IMAGE_DEF_NAME \
  --query "osState" -o tsv)

echo "   OS State: $OS_STATE"

if [[ "$OS_STATE" != "Generalized" ]]; then
  echo "⚠️ This script only validates GENERALIZED images. Your image is $OS_STATE."
  exit 1
fi

echo ">> Checking if VM Agent is installed in the image..."
# NOTE: ACG itself doesn’t store “agent installed” metadata.
# Trick: Deploy a temporary specialized VM from same VHD & check agent.

TEMP_VM="AgentCheckVM"

echo ">> Creating temporary specialized VM from same VHD to test agent..."
az vm create \
  --resource-group $RG_NAME \
  --name $TEMP_VM \
  --image $ACG_IMAGE_ID \
  --specialized \
  --size $SIZE \
  --enable-agent true \
  --verbose

sleep 60

AGENT_STATUS=$(az vm get-instance-view \
  --resource-group $RG_NAME \
  --name $TEMP_VM \
  --query "instanceView.vmAgent.statuses[0].displayStatus" -o tsv)

echo "   VM Agent Status: $AGENT_STATUS"

if [[ "$AGENT_STATUS" != "Ready" ]]; then
  echo "❌ VM Agent is not healthy or not installed. Generalized provisioning WILL FAIL."
  echo "   Fix by installing waagent (Linux) or checking Windows Azure Agent + Sysprep."
  # Cleanup temp VM
  az vm delete -n $TEMP_VM -g $RG_NAME --yes --no-wait
  exit 1
fi

# Cleanup temp VM
az vm delete -n $TEMP_VM -g $RG_NAME --yes --no-wait

echo "✅ VM Agent healthy. Proceeding to provisioning test..."

echo ">> Creating VM from generalized ACG image..."
az vm create \
  --resource-group $RG_NAME \
  --name $VM_NAME \
  --image $ACG_IMAGE_ID \
  --admin-username $USER \
  --admin-password $PASSWORD \
  --size $SIZE \
  --authentication-type password \
  --verbose

sleep 60

PROV_STATE=$(az vm get-instance-view \
  --resource-group $RG_NAME \
  --name $VM_NAME \
  --query "instanceView.statuses[?starts_with(code,'ProvisioningState/')].displayStatus" -o tsv)

echo "======================================="
echo "Provisioning State: $PROV_STATE"
echo "======================================="

if [[ "$PROV_STATE" == "Provisioning succeeded" ]]; then
  echo "✅ VM provisioned successfully from generalized ACG image"
else
  echo "❌ VM provisioning failed (likely generalization/agent issue)"
fi

# Optional cleanup
read -p "Do you want to delete the test resource group $RG_NAME? (y/n): " confirm
if [[ $confirm == "y" ]]; then
  echo ">> Deleting resource group..."
  az group delete -n $RG_NAME --yes --no-wait
fi
🔹 What Changed
Check ACG image definition’s osState → prevents wrong testing.

Temporary specialized VM check → validates if VM Agent is installed and reporting Ready.

If agent missing → script stops early (no wasted provisioning attempt).

Provisioning test → only runs if agent is healthy.

⚡ This way you can reliably detect:

If the ACG image was created as generalized.

If the agent is installed and functional.

If the VM provisions successfully.

