You said:
First we should check acg imgage is generalized and then should create vm but vm creation will fail if generalized since it will try to expect agent installed then what should be solution for this problem where acg image would be generalized
ChatGPT said:
Great question 👍 — you’re hitting the core issue with generalized ACG images.

Let me break it down:

🔹 Why VM creation fails from generalized ACG image
When osState=Generalized is set in the ACG image definition, Azure assumes:

The OS has been generalized (sysprep for Windows, waagent -deprovision+user for Linux).

The Azure VM Agent is installed and running inside the OS.

During VM creation from this image, Azure injects credentials, hostname, provisioning data via the agent.

If the agent isn’t installed, or the OS wasn’t properly generalized → Azure can’t complete provisioning → ❌ VM creation fails with timeout.

🔹 Solution
✅ Correct way to build a generalized ACG image
Start from a working VM created from your managed disk.

Install the Azure VM Agent inside it:

Linux:

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install walinuxagent -y
sudo systemctl enable waagent
sudo systemctl restart waagent
Windows: Azure Agent is usually preinstalled; if not → install WindowsAzureGuestAgent.msi.

Generalize the OS:

Linux:

sudo waagent -deprovision+user
sudo shutdown -h now
Windows: Run sysprep /generalize /oobe /shutdown.

Capture to ACG as generalized:

az sig image-version create \
  --resource-group MyRG \
  --gallery-name MyGallery \
  --gallery-image-definition MyImageDef \
  --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \
  --managed-image "/subscriptions/.../resourceGroups/.../providers/Microsoft.Compute/images/MyGeneralizedImage"
Create VM from generalized ACG image (Azure will now succeed because agent is alive + OS is generalized).

🚑 If you already have a generalized ACG image but it fails
That means the source VM was not prepared correctly. Options:

Rebuild the image properly (recommended, steps above).

Or, if you cannot rebuild, capture it as a specialized image instead (--os-state specialized). Then VM creation won’t rely on the agent. But → you lose flexibility (no username/password injection, must log in with original credentials baked into the VM).

✅ Summary

Generalized ACG images must have both Agent + Generalization.

If missing → rebuild the image properly.

If you don’t want that, use specialized ACG instead.

